Engine may stall, FAA urgently orders 2000 Boeing airliners-Xinhuanet
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of approximately 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737Classic airliners registered in the United States. The reason is that the corrosion of the air check valves of the airliners may cause the engine to fly in the air. parking.
The Federal Aviation Administration said that it has received 4 reports of 737NG and 737Classic aircraft engines stopping in the air, so it has made urgent inspection requirements. The inspection objects are passenger aircraft that have been parked for 7 consecutive days or more and the number of flights has been less than 11 so far after being re-commissioned. Airliner.
The FAA warned that if the level 5 check valves of all two engines of the airliner are corroded, they may become stuck in the open position, causing the airliner to completely lose power and unable to restart the engine.
The aviation regulatory agency ordered that once the check valve is found to be corroded, the aviation operator must replace this key component before the passenger plane is put into service again.
Boeing responded later that day that the outbreak of the new crown epidemic has reduced travel demand, and many passenger aircraft have been sealed or used less frequently, and "check valves are more likely to be corroded."
At the same time, Boeing said that it has advised air operators to inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the order. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in maintenance and replacement of check valves.
The Associated Press reported that airlines owned by major U.S. airlines usually fly multiple times in a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of airliners were grounded; as passenger travel demand has grown slowly recently, some airliners have been put back into operation.
The FAA did not release the details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline said in a statement that on July 15th, one of its passenger planes was en route from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas, when an engine suddenly turned off, and the passenger plane finally made an emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines stated that it had replaced the airliner's engine and had inspected the engines of six airliners in accordance with FAA instructions.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that there was no engine stalling associated with the air check valve on their airliners.
Four airliners under American Airlines will be inspected, and 28 airliners under United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 passenger planes, but did not say whether there had been engine stalls.
Many media reported that the FAA's emergency airworthiness directive was another impact on Boeing.
Indonesia Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines each crashed a Boeing 737MAX passenger plane in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger aircraft was subsequently grounded globally, production was suspended in January this year, and production resumed in May.
FAA Director Steve Dixon admitted in June that the FAA "made a mistake" in its supervision of Boeing regarding the 737MAX airliner.
