APEC member trade ministers meeting said it will accelerate regional economic recovery-Xinhua English.news.cn
Xinhua News Agency, Kuala Lumpur, July 25 (Reporter Lin Hao) A video conference of APEC trade ministers was held on the 25th. The meeting promised to work to reduce the impact of the new crown epidemic on the regional economy and accelerate the realization of flexibility and sustainability And inclusive regional economic recovery.
The meeting was hosted by Malaysia, the host of this year's APEC informal leaders' meeting.
The joint statement issued after the meeting stated that APEC member trade ministers recognize the importance of a free, open, fair, non-discriminatory, transparent and predictable trade and investment environment to promote economic recovery at this challenging time. .
All parties pledged to ensure that the emergency measures taken in response to the epidemic are targeted, appropriate, transparent and temporary, and will not create unnecessary trade barriers and disrupt the global supply chain, while complying with the rules of the World Trade Organization.
In the statement, APEC member trade ministers promised to strengthen cooperation to promote the flow of necessary goods and services, promote interconnection by strengthening the flexibility of the supply chain, and minimize the interference in the flow of medical supplies, food and agricultural products in response to the epidemic.
APEC member trade ministers agreed that it is necessary to discuss how to reduce non-tariff barriers that restrict the trade of necessary commodities, and reiterated their commitment to promoting the necessary cross-border movement of people without affecting the measures taken to prevent the spread of the epidemic.
The meeting also issued a declaration on promoting the circulation of necessary commodities.
The declaration stated that the economies will ensure that the trade measures they take in response to the epidemic are in compliance with WTO regulations, and pledged to take actions in reducing non-tariff trade barriers and trade promotion to promote the flow of necessary commodities during the epidemic.
The Minister of International Trade and Industry of Malaysia, Azmin Ali, who presided over the meeting, said that despite the impact of the epidemic, Malaysia is still committed to promoting the success of this year's APEC meeting, and the work of formulating a vision for APEC cooperation after 2020 is progressing in an orderly manner.
Malaysia has agreed to hold APEC-related meetings in the form of video, but does not rule out the possibility of arranging physical meetings at the end of the APEC informal meeting of leaders.
