France increases military investment in space-Xinhuanet
French Defense Minister Florence Parley said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget to develop space military forces to prevent "unfriendly moves" that other countries may make in outer space.
Parley told the Provence newspaper that between 2019 and 2025, the expenditure budget for French space military projects will increase from the previously planned 3.6 billion euros (approximately 4.2 billion US dollars) to 4.3 billion euros (5 billion US dollars).
According to the French Military Planning Act from 2019 to 2025 approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to update its existing observation satellites and communication satellites in the future, launch 3 electromagnetic detection satellites, and improve the modernization level of space surveillance radars.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced in July last year that the French Air Force will establish a space military command and an "Aviation and Space Force."
Parley said that she will formally announce the establishment of the space force when she visits a military academy in Salon, Provence.
Parley said that this space force is affiliated to the Air Force and will have 500 personnel by 2025.
She said: "In the past, people thought that space serves the common interests of science. This idea is gone forever. Now space is a place where countries compete for global hegemony."
Parley reiterated Macron's previous statement, saying that France has no intention to provoke an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to thoroughly recognize the threats we may face."
Parley revisited the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said that the "spy" was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denies this statement.
Parley said that France "soon" will have small patrol satellites that can detect and lock "the black hands behind those unfriendly actions."
French media believe that the reason why France is seeking to establish a space force is due to US President Donald Trump's request in February last year that the US Department of Defense draft a bill to establish a space force.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act in December last year, approving the establishment of the sixth largest U.S. service, the Space Force.
Some experts worry that these US measures have accelerated the pace of US space militarization and may trigger a new round of space arms race.
