The report says the shared accommodation market has picked up since March-Xinhua English.news.cn
News from our newspaper (Reporter Yang Zhaokui) The "China Shared Accommodation Development Report 2020" (hereinafter referred to as the "Report") released by the National Information Center Sharing Economy Research Center recently shows that, affected by the epidemic, the first 5 months of 2020, my country's shared accommodation market transactions The amount decreased by 72.1% year-on-year.
However, the shared accommodation market began to pick up in March, and the market transaction volume, order volume and number of receptions gradually recovered.
The "Report" shows that the transaction volume of the shared accommodation market has dropped sharply. On the one hand, due to the sharp decline in the demand for travel accommodation under the epidemic prevention and control, the order volume has dropped sharply. The total number of orders in the first 5 months has dropped by 65% year-on-year, and the number of receptions has dropped by 63% year-on-year. On the other hand, the weak demand has also led to a relatively significant drop in room night prices. The average room night price in the first five months fell 16% year-on-year.
However, in March, April, and May, the market transaction volume increased by 78%, 199%, and 35%, respectively; the number of orders increased by 141%, 152%, and 50%, respectively; and the number of visitors increased by 81%, 112%, and 112%, respectively. 28%.
The "Report" pointed out that the development of the shared accommodation industry is promising for a long time, but there are still many uncertainties in the near future.
In this regard, Yu Fengxia, deputy director of the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center, told the Workers’ Daily reporter that the development of shared accommodation requires stronger policy support. We must focus on creating a better business environment; on the other hand, we need to further increase policy guidance and support in terms of stimulating consumer demand, enriching the supply of tourism accommodation services, innovating service methods, and strengthening cooperation between the government and platform companies .
