Is it reasonable for a 3-year-old child to be smashed while playing in the college playground.
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, and the child was compensated before suing the school
□ Correspondent Zhao Yifan
The 3-year-old Xiaowen was accidentally hit in the head by Chen of the softball team while playing in the playground of a certain university.
After Chen made the compensation, Xiaowen's father, Mr. Wen, served as Xiaowen's legal representative to the school to the court, demanding an apology from the school where the incident occurred, and payment of medical expenses, mental damage relief, etc. totaling 20,000 yuan.
Recently, after hearing the case, the People’s Court of Haidian District of Beijing held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident, and that it had fulfilled its obligations to ensure proper safety, and Chen had already paid compensation. Based on this judgment, the plaintiff’s decision was rejected. Claims.
Mr. Wen claimed that he took Xiaowen to play on the school playground during the summer vacation of 2019, when the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks posed by this, Xiaowen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents play in safe areas designated by the softball team.
But then the softball player Chen dropped his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the guard net into the above-mentioned safe area and hit the back of Xiaowen's head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the school stadium facilities do not comply with relevant safety regulations, and the team and related facilities have not been effectively managed.
The school’s negligence caused the above incidents to occur, which caused Xiaowen to suffer tremendous physical and mental pain, and at the same time brought greater pain to his family. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground, and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that entering the playground must keep a safe distance from the training site and reminding their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school was “not enough. "Safety guarantee obligation", so I do not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the site involved in the incident was a site open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a safety guarantee obligation for the management of the playground, this safety guarantee obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net on the playground, and has fulfilled its proper safety guarantee obligations. Chen also compensated Xiaowen for various losses including medical expenses and transportation expenses in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement. Both parties It is agreed that this dispute will be resolved at one time.
After the incident, Xiaowen's parents again claimed compensation from the school. There was no basis in the law. The court ruled that all the plaintiff's claims were rejected.
After the verdict was pronounced, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of my country’s Tort Liability Law, schools, as managers of public places, have the obligation to ensure safety; in the event that the actions of a third party cause damage to others, the third party bears tort liability, but the safety protection is not fulfilled. The responsible public place manager shall bear corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
The judge stated that as a manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place and foresee possible dangers and damages, so that he is most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the extent of damage, and to avoid and mitigate them. The cost of damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that it shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligations for engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified people entering the playground that is free to the public, the school’s safety guarantee obligations should be compatible with the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should take basic safety measures and deal with hidden dangers. Have the obligation to inform.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety guarantee obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation of notification, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringements, even if the administrators of public places such as schools fail to fulfill their obligations to ensure safety, their liability is a supplement to compensation for damages. According to the latest civil code, after the administrator assumes additional liability, You can also claim compensation from a third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victims should not expand the scope of compensation after they have received compensation from the direct infringer.
